    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-08-07T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-08-07T19:00:00-05:00" n="566"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d566">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">785.00/8–551: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Embassy in Saudi Arabia</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d566fn1">Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_JGL1"
                            >Jones</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_SW1">Stabler</persName>
                            (<gloss target="#t_NE1">NE</gloss>) and cleared by <persName
                            corresp="#p_MGC2">McGhee</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <gloss target="#t_niact1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">niact</hi>
                        </gloss>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-08-07T20:00:00-04:00"
                            >August 7, 1951—8 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>49. Msg along fol lines shld be conveyed to King in reply his msg (<gloss
                        target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 68, Aug 5):<note n="2" xml:id="d566fn2"
                        >Not printed. In it, King <persName corresp="#p_IAA1">Saud</persName>
                        expressed concern over reports that Iraq and Syria were acting to
                        incorporate the territory of Transjordan. The King expressed the hope that
                        the United States would help maintain the <hi rend="italic">status quo</hi>
                        in regard to Transjordan. (785.00/8–551)</note>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_USG1">USG</gloss> grateful for <gloss target="#t_HM1"
                        >HM</gloss>’s views on present situation in <gloss target="#t_NE1"
                        >NE</gloss> arising from tragic death of King <persName corresp="#p_AH1"
                        >Abdullah</persName> and as is well known to <gloss target="#t_HM1"
                        >HM</gloss>, shares his deep concern for maintenance tranquillity and
                    stability in area. It is hoped by <gloss target="#t_USG1">USG</gloss> that
                    people of Jordan will be permitted to work out whatever destiny they may choose
                    in calm, deliberative atmosphere. The United States wld look with disfavor upon
                    any change in status of the sovereign states of the <gloss target="#t_NE1"
                        >NE</gloss> brought about by force or external intervention. At the same
                    time it is cardinal principle of American policy to respect right of peoples
                    freely to choose their own form of government. <gloss target="#t_HM1">HM</gloss>
                    may be sure that US will continue to follow developments in <gloss
                        target="#t_NE1">NE</gloss> carefully and will not fail to give this matter
                    careful consideration which it merits.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_ADG1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
